CH. LXI. barbaro voto] Scratch a Batavian, and you soon found a Chattan‚ 12. 2, Germ. 29. 1. In Germ. 31. 1 we are told that this custom of letting the hair grow till they had slain an enemy, adopted by individuals throughout Germany, was universal among the Chatti. Caesar in Gaul once did the same, by way of a vow to avenge the defeat of Titurius and Cotta by Ambiorix. The same practice, or similar ones, have been found in half civilised races in both earlier and later times —e.g. the Scotch loyalists who, in the seventeenth and eighteenth cen· turies, ‘ wore a beard for the king.'
